<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN COURT: A SUMMARY OF SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA-RELATED BUSINESS LITIGATION 
DEVELOPMENTS DURING THE PAST WEEK. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Former Thrift Chairman Pleads Innocent: Oliver A. Trigg Jr., the former 
chairman of Family Federal Savings Bank, one of the nation's largest 
black-owned thrifts, pleaded innocent to charges that he masterminded an 
elaborate scheme to buy Family with its own money. 
</P>
<P>
Trigg and two associates, James E. Williams and William A. Powell, denied any 
wrongdoing in Trigg's purchase of a controlling interest in the thrift for 
$1.24 million in 1987. Prosecutors said the scheme was carried out through a 
series of real estate transactions. Trial is scheduled for Nov. 20. If 
convicted on all counts, Trigg faces up to 94 years in prison and a $1-million 
fine. (Case No. 90-698. Pleas Entered Oct. 8). 
</P>
</TEXT>
